    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
            <ab><lb n="1"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Castorinus">Castorinus</name></persName> <expan><abbr>mi<choice><corr>l</corr><sic>t</sic></choice></abbr><ex>es</ex></expan>;
                <lb n="2"/>utere felix.</ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Castorinus the soldier; may you use [it] well.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The individual who presumably owned the pin, Castorinus, is noted by only one name.
                    He is further described as a miles, or a soldier. The inscription, utere felix,
                    is attested on a number of personal objects from across the empire, but
                    especially in Britain. The inscription, particularly the imperative nature of
                    utere, indicates that this was likely a gift rather than being inscribed, or
                    paid for, by Castorinus himself. The double-sided nature
                    of the pin allows for only one half of the message to be visible while the pin
                    is being worn: this might suggest the inscription was private in nature.</p></div>
            

